{"title_page": "Daryl Katz", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Daryl Katz\n| image       = 2010 NHL Entry Draft 011-Kat.jpg \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Daryl Katz at the [[2010 NHL Entry Draft]]\n| birth_name  = Daryl Allan Katz\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1961|5|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| residence   = Edmonton, Alberta\n| education   = \n| alma_mater  = [[University of Alberta]]\n| occupation  = Chairman and CEO of the [[Katz Group]]\n| known_for   = Owner of the [[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| networth    = [[United States dollar|US $]] 3.1 [[1,000,000,000 (number)|billion]]<br/>(May 2019)<ref name=ForbesBillionaires>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/daryl-katz |title=Forbes profile: Daryl Katz |website=Forbes.com |date=|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse      = Renee Gouin\n| children    = 2\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Daryl Allan Katz''' (born May 31, 1961) is a Canadian [[billionaire]] businessman  and philanthropist. Katz is founder and chairman of the [[Katz Group of Companies]], one of Canada's largest privately owned enterprises, with pharmacy, sports & entertainment, and real estate development businesses. Katz Group owns the [[Edmonton Oilers]], and lead the development of [[Rogers Place]] and the Ice District.  Katz is a former lawyer, and resides in Edmonton.\n\n==Early life==\nDaryl Katz was born in 1961 in Edmonton, Alberta.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121216090649/http://www.edmontonjournal.com/opinion/blogs/Daryl+Katz+reclusive+billionaire/7701358/story.html ]</ref> His father was a pharmacist who founded [[Value Drug Mart]] in Edmonton in the 1970s.<ref name=ArchivesCanada /> Katz attended the Jewish day school, [[Talmud Torah]] School during his elementary years and then graduated from [[Jasper Place High School]].<ref name=ArchivesCanada>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131111055102/http://www.archivescanada.ca/english/search/ItemDisplay.asp?sessionKey=999999999_142&l=0&lvl=1&v=0&coll=1&itm=248122&rt=1&bill=1 ]</ref><ref name=EdmontonJournalReclusive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131005111141/http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/insight/story.html?id=25433850-1494-4be2-a74e-8ba819d6465c&p=1]</ref>  He then attended the [[University of Alberta]], graduating with an arts degree in 1982 and with a law degree in 1985.<ref name=ArchivesCanada/>\n\n==Pharmacy business==\nAfter school, he worked for a time at the law firm, Shoctor, Mousseau and Starkman,<ref name=ArchivesCanada/> and then started his own practice focusing on corporate and franchise law. In 1991, in a partnership with his father, Katz paid $300,000 for the Canadian rights to the U.S.-based Medicine Shoppe drugstore franchise which had over 1,000 stores in the USA. In 1992, they opened the first Medicine Shoppe store and Katz founded the Katz Group of Companies which was to become the holding company for the group. In 1996, Katz purchased the storied but fading [[Rexall]] drugstore chain in Canada which at the time, only consisted of several dozen stores. The business grew and by 1998, the Katz Group consisted of 80 Rexall stores, 30 Medicine Shoppe outlets, and a few smaller independent retailers. In 1997, he purchased the Ontario-based, 143-store Pharma Plus drug store chain from the supermarket operator [[Oshawa Group]] for $100 million.<ref name=EdmontonJournalReclusive/> Katz reportedly retains a small circle of highly paid executives who run Katz Group. Rexall Pharmacy is run from Ontario, while other subsidiaries of Katz Group maintain private headquarters separate from Katz Group itself.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100418223259/http://64.141.115.51/cgi-bin/press_katz.pl?record=36 ]</ref>\n\nIn 1999 he ventured into the U.S. with the purchase of the money-losing, $300 million in sales, Minnesota-based Snyders Drug Store chain; in 2001, he purchased the U.S.-based [[Drug Emporium]] big-box discount chain. His foray into the U.S. was not without failure: the Snyder's chain filed for bankruptcy in 2003 and its 25 stores were sold to Walgreens. In 2004, Katz purchased the naming rights for ten years to the new $45-million [[Rexall Centre]], a 12,500-seat tennis and entertainment complex on the campus of York University. In January 2012, he sold Drug Trading Co. and Medicine Shoppe Canada to the U.S.-based drug distributor [[McKesson Corporation]] for $1.2 billion. Katz Group retained its network of approximately 460 corporate-owned 450 Rexall-branded outlets.<ref name=EdmontonJournalReclusive/>\n\n==Purchase of Edmonton Oilers and Creation of Oilers Entertainment Group (OEG)==\nIn May 2007, Katz made a $145-million bid to buy the [[Edmonton Oilers]] franchise, which the owners of the team, the [[Edmonton Investors Group]] (EIG), quickly rejected, stating the team was not for sale.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn July 2007, he made another bid for the Oilers of $185-million, which EIG turned down on August 7, 2007.<ref name=\"Buying Oilers\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/oilers-not-for-sale-owners-tell-billionaire-suitor-1.638074|title=Oilers not for sale, owners tell billionaire suitor|accessdate=2007-08-07|publisher=CBC.ca|author=CBC News | date=August 7, 2007}}</ref> On December 12, 2007, Katz made an offer of $188-million to the EIG. The Board of the EIG announced in January 2008 that it would again recommend to its shareholders to reject this latest bid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2008/01/02/oilers-reject.html |title=Edmonton Oilers' owners to reject tycoon's latest offer - Edmonton - CBC News |website=Cbc.ca |date=2008-01-02 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2008, Katz increased his offer to $200 million and extended the acceptance deadline to February 5, 2008, at which time Katz was notified by the EIG that all its members agreed to sell the Oilers to him, pending league and financial approval.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080207054010/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=228952&hubname= ]</ref> On June 18, 2008, Daryl Katz received the final OK from the National Hockey League to purchase the Edmonton Oilers, and then on July 2, 2008, he was officially announced as the owner of the Edmonton Oilers during a Press Conference at Rexall Place, where he was presented with an Edmonton Oilers Jersey with the number \"08\" and his last name patched onto the back.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn June 2014, Katz Group announced<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=722586#&navid=EDM-search |title=Katz Group Names Bob Nicholson Vice-Chairman of New Sports & Entertainment Company &#124; NHL.com |website=Oilers.nhl.com |date=2014-06-13 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> that [[Bob Nicholson (ice hockey)|Bob Nicholson]] would join the organization as Vice-Chairman of [[Oilers Entertainment Group]] (OEG), a new sports and entertainment company that would manage the Katz Group's growing family of sports and entertainment assets, and operate [[Rogers Place]], the new home of the Edmonton Oilers.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn addition to the Oilers, OEG owns and operates the [[Edmonton Oil Kings]] (WHL), and [[Bakersfield Condors (AHL)|Bakersfield Condors]] (AHL) as well as Aquila Productions (film & production company). Nicholson was named<ref>{{cite web|title=Edmonton Oilers Press Release|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=764212|website=Oilers.nhl.com|publisher=NHL|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> CEO of OEG in April 2015 and given responsibility for both business and hockey operations.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn April 2015, Katz announced a partnership<ref>{{cite web|last=Hipes |first=Patrick |url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/joel-silver-silver-pictures-entertainment-daryl-katz-hal-sadoff-1201416892/ |title=Joel Silver Forms Silver Pictures Entertainment & Taps Hal Sadoff As CEO |publisher=Deadline |date=2015-04-27 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> with [[Joel Silver]] to create Silver Pictures Entertainment \u2013 a new company that will develop, produce and provide or arrange financing for feature films, television and digital projects.  Katz\u2019 interests in the company fall under the OEG umbrella.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Rogers Place and Edmonton Ice District (former Arena District)==\nKatz has said he bought the Oilers because he saw Edmonton's need for a new arena as an opportunity to be the catalyst for the revitalization of Edmonton's downtown core.  Following public consultations and negotiations with the [[City of Edmonton]], Katz Group and the city agreed to a public-private partnership to build Rogers Place arena, which would see the city retain ownership of the new arena, and Katz Group operate it (under OEG). The City's portion of arena funding will be paid through a Community Revitalization Levy and will not result in any new cost to taxpayers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Funding Agreement |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/the-agreement.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712155036/http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/the-agreement.aspx |archivedate=2015-07-12 }}</ref>  Construction on the project began March 2014.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nSet to open in fall 2016, Rogers Place was marketed as one of North America's most advanced sports & entertainment venues, active year-round and featuring a 24,000 square foot grand entrance-way called the Winter Garden which can be used as public/private programmable space.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winter Garden |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/arena-winter-garden.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507151321/http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/arena-winter-garden.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-07 }}</ref>\n\nWith Rogers Place at its core, Katz Group has begun construction of the Edmonton Arena District (EAD),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=80301 |title=Edmonton Downtown Arena and Entertainment District - Edmonton Oilers - News |website=Oilers.nhl.com |date=2012-05-17 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> slated to be Canada's largest mixed-use sports and entertainment development. The EAD will cover 25 contiguous acres of downtown Edmonton, and feature a 50,000 square foot public plaza, two office towers, a JW Marriott Hotel, a Gateway casino, over 1,000 luxury condos and rental apartments, and 270,000 square feet of retail space at a total cost of approximately $2.5 billion.  In 2014, it was announced that the City of Edmonton and [[Stantec]] would be the major tenants of the two respective office towers. Stantec's tower will be the tallest in Edmonton at 69 storeys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/62-storey-tower-to-be-built-in-downtown-edmonton-1.2747702 |title=62-storey tower to be built in downtown Edmonton - Edmonton - CBC News |website=Cbc.ca |date=2014-08-26 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Edmonton Arena District was formally renamed the [[Ice District]] on July 13, 2015.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn October 2006 Katz announced a $7 million donation to the University of Alberta Faculty of Pharmacy and Pharmaceutical Sciences and Faculty of Law. Matched by the province, the gift was the largest donation ever to a Canadian pharmacy school. The west wing of the Health Research Innovation Facility at the corner of 87th Avenue and 114th Street in Edmonton has been named The Katz Group Centre for Pharmacy and Health Research. In 2009 Katz donated $20 Million to [[Mount Sinai Hospital in Toronto]] and founded The Daryl A Katz Centre For Urgent And Critical Care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mshfoundation.ca/page.aspx?pid=424 |title=Mount Sinai Hospital Foundation of Toronto |website=Mshfoundation.ca |date=2014-01-20 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> Katz has also given \"millions\" to the [[Stollery Children's Hospital]] in Edmonton, as well as supporting public events.<ref name=\"tsn.ca\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100524113236/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=322173]</ref>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2010, Katz and his wife have donated \"over $50 million\" to organizations and institutions across Canada.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121110160305/http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=a34af8e9-099d-4175-8c35-d81d4364b32f&sponsor= ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/travel/Daryl+Renee+Katz+donate+Gallery+Alberta/2491478/story.html |title=Daryl and Renee Katz donate $500,000 to Art Gallery of Alberta |website=Edmontonjournal.com |date=2010-01-27 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKatz' [[net worth]] is reported at US$3.5 billion which makes him the 12th wealthiest person in Canada.<ref name=ForbesBillionaires/>\n\nKatz is married to Renee Gouin.<ref name=ArchivesCanada />  She is the daughter of [[Jean Ivan Gouin|Jean Yvon (Ivan) Gouin]]. In 1952, her father founded the North American Construction Group which became one of the largest mining and heavy construction companies in Canada.<ref>[http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/insight/story.html?id=25433850-1494-4be2-a74e-8ba819d6465c&p=1   He has two kids: Chlo\u00e9 Katz and Harrison Katz. They both started a new organization in 2015 called Hockey Helps Kids.  The organization was meant for 4 junior high school to make a video and then it would be showed at Oiler games and people would vote on their favourite school. The school that wins will receive $25,000 for their charity. The three other schools would get $10 000 for their charity and $5000 for their school.  The schools were also given a team captain which were one of the Oilers players. The captains for 2015/2016 were Connor McDavid, Jordan Eberle, Taylor Hall, and Ryan Nugent-Hopkins. The winners of 2015/2016 were Kilarny school with captain Connor McDavid. ''Edmonton Journal'': \"Daryl Katz: reclusive billionaire\" by Rick McConnell, John MacKinnon and Gary Lamphier] December 17, 2012 \\ ''\"Katz married Renee Gouin, a member of one of Edmonton's wealthiest families...Her parents, Jean Yvon and Carol Gouin, had started a Spruce Grove company called North American Construction Group in 1952, which they built into one of the largest mining and heavy construction companies in Canada\"''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/remembering/obituary.aspx?n=jean-yvon-gouin-ivan&pid=98838924#fbLoggedOut |title=Jean Gouin Obituary - Vancouver, BC &#124; Remembering |website=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nKatz's riverfront mansion at 4 Valleyview Point in the [[Parkview, Edmonton|Parkview neighbourhood]], is one of the largest houses in Edmonton at {{convert|25000|sqft|m2}}, and estimated to be worth C$13 million.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gordon Kent |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/business/real-estate/property-values-on-the-rise-in-edmonton |title=Top homes worth a bundle in Edmonton millionaire\u2019s market |newspaper=[[Edmonton Journal]] |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>  The property overlooks the [[North Saskatchewan River valley parks system|North Saskatchewan river valley]], [[Hawrelak Park]], and the downtown city skyline and is easily visible and instantly recognizable from the river valley's many trails.  The [[great room]] is clad floor-to-ceiling in {{convert|90|kg|adj=on}} blocks of Italian [[limestone]] and with {{convert|9|m|adj=on}}-high windows framing a view of downtown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communities.canada.com/edmontonjournal/blogs/hockey/archive/2008/02/06/daryl-katz-may-be-a-caped-crusader-but-he-is-no-bruce-wayne.aspx |title=Tonic to some, bitter pill to others: Daryl Katz's 25,000-square-foot mansion demands--and gets--attention, both pro and con |accessdate=2008-06-04 |author=Shawn Ohler |date=May 21, 2006 |work=The [[Edmonton Journal]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610165109/http://communities.canada.com/edmontonjournal/blogs/hockey/archive/2008/02/06/daryl-katz-may-be-a-caped-crusader-but-he-is-no-bruce-wayne.aspx |archivedate=2008-06-10 }}</ref> The property also features two swimming pools. For his children, Katz bought the multimillion-dollar house next to his, demolished it, and built a practice hockey rink.\n\nKatz also owns homes in the US and British Columbia, the latter reportedly a near carbon copy of his Edmonton home.<ref name=\"tsn.ca\"/>\n\nIt was reported in May 2019 that Katz had had a \"potentially life-threatening infection\" for a few years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/edmonton-oilers-daryl-katz-illness-1.5126650|title=Edmonton Oilers owner Daryl Katz dealing with life-threatening illness, team says}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.katzgroup.ca/ The Katz Group of Companies]\n\n{{Katz Group}}\n{{Edmonton Oilers}}\n{{NHLOwners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katz, Daryl}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Katz Group]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Canadian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Canadian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Canadian investors]]\n[[Category:Canadian pharmaceutical industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Oilers executives]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Alberta]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League executives]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League owners]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta Faculty of Law alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Daryl Katz\n| image       = 2010 NHL Entry Draft 011-Kat.jpg \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Daryl Katz at the [[2010 NHL Entry Draft]]\n| birth_name  = Daryl Allan Katz\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1961|5|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| residence   = Edmonton, Alberta\n| education   = \n| alma_mater  = [[University of Alberta]]\n| occupation  = Chairman and CEO of the [[Katz Group]]\n| known_for   = Owner of the [[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| networth    = [[United States dollar|US $]] 3.1 [[1,000,000,000 (number)|billion]]<br/>(May 2019)<ref name=ForbesBillionaires>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/daryl-katz |title=Forbes profile: Daryl Katz |website=Forbes.com |date=|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse      = Renee Gouin\n| children    = 2\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Daryl Allan Katz''' (born May 31, 1961) is a Canadian [[billionaire]] businessman  and philanthropist. Katz is founder and chairman of the [[Katz Group of Companies]], one of Canada's largest privately owned enterprises, with pharmacy, sports & entertainment, and real estate development businesses. Katz Group owns the [[Edmonton Oilers]], and lead the development of [[Rogers Place]] and the Ice District.  Katz is a former lawyer, and resides in Edmonton.\n\n==Early life==\nDaryl Katz was born in 1961 in Edmonton, Alberta.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121216090649/http://www.edmontonjournal.com/opinion/blogs/Daryl+Katz+reclusive+billionaire/7701358/story.html ]</ref> His father was a pharmacist who founded [[Value Drug Mart]] in Edmonton in the 1970s.<ref name=ArchivesCanada /> Katz attended the Jewish day school, [[Talmud Torah]] School during his elementary years and then graduated from [[Jasper Place High School]].<ref name=ArchivesCanada>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131111055102/http://www.archivescanada.ca/english/search/ItemDisplay.asp?sessionKey=999999999_142&l=0&lvl=1&v=0&coll=1&itm=248122&rt=1&bill=1 ]</ref><ref name=EdmontonJournalReclusive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131005111141/http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/insight/story.html?id=25433850-1494-4be2-a74e-8ba819d6465c&p=1]</ref>  He then attended the [[University of Alberta]], graduating with an arts degree in 1982 and with a law degree in 1985.<ref name=ArchivesCanada/>\n\n==Pharmacy business==\nAfter school, he worked for a time at the law firm, Shoctor, Mousseau and Starkman,<ref name=ArchivesCanada/> and then started his own practice focusing on corporate and franchise law. In 1991, in a partnership with his father, Katz paid $300,000 for the Canadian rights to the U.S.-based Medicine Shoppe drugstore franchise which had over 1,000 stores in the USA. In 1992, they opened the first Medicine Shoppe store and Katz founded the Katz Group of Companies which was to become the holding company for the group. In 1996, Katz purchased the storied but fading [[Rexall]] drugstore chain in Canada which at the time, only consisted of several dozen stores. The business grew and by 1998, the Katz Group consisted of 80 Rexall stores, 30 Medicine Shoppe outlets, and a few smaller independent retailers. In 1997, he purchased the Ontario-based, 143-store Pharma Plus drug store chain from the supermarket operator [[Oshawa Group]] for $100 million.<ref name=EdmontonJournalReclusive/> Katz reportedly retains a small circle of highly paid executives who run Katz Group. Rexall Pharmacy is run from Ontario, while other subsidiaries of Katz Group maintain private headquarters separate from Katz Group itself.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100418223259/http://64.141.115.51/cgi-bin/press_katz.pl?record=36 ]</ref>\n\nIn 1999 he ventured into the U.S. with the purchase of the money-losing, $300 million in sales, Minnesota-based Snyders Drug Store chain; in 2001, he purchased the U.S.-based [[Drug Emporium]] big-box discount chain. His foray into the U.S. was not without failure: the Snyder's chain filed for bankruptcy in 2003 and its 25 stores were sold to Walgreens. In 2004, Katz purchased the naming rights for ten years to the new $45-million [[Rexall Centre]], a 12,500-seat tennis and entertainment complex on the campus of York University. In January 2012, he sold Drug Trading Co. and Medicine Shoppe Canada to the U.S.-based drug distributor [[McKesson Corporation]] for $1.2 billion. Katz Group retained its network of approximately 460 corporate-owned 450 Rexall-branded outlets.<ref name=EdmontonJournalReclusive/>\n\n==Purchase of Edmonton Oilers and Creation of Oilers Entertainment Group (OEG)==\nIn May 2007, Katz made a $145-million bid to buy the [[Edmonton Oilers]] franchise, which the owners of the team, the [[Edmonton Investors Group]] (EIG), quickly rejected, stating the team was not for sale.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn July 2007, he made another bid for the Oilers of $185-million, which EIG turned down on August 7, 2007.<ref name=\"Buying Oilers\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/oilers-not-for-sale-owners-tell-billionaire-suitor-1.638074|title=Oilers not for sale, owners tell billionaire suitor|accessdate=2007-08-07|publisher=CBC.ca|author=CBC News | date=August 7, 2007}}</ref> On December 12, 2007, Katz made an offer of $188-million to the EIG. The Board of the EIG announced in January 2008 that it would again recommend to its shareholders to reject this latest bid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2008/01/02/oilers-reject.html |title=Edmonton Oilers' owners to reject tycoon's latest offer - Edmonton - CBC News |website=Cbc.ca |date=2008-01-02 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 2008, Katz increased his offer to $200 million and extended the acceptance deadline to February 5, 2008, at which time Katz was notified by the EIG that all its members agreed to sell the Oilers to him, pending league and financial approval.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080207054010/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/news_story/?ID=228952&hubname= ]</ref> On June 18, 2008, Daryl Katz received the final OK from the National Hockey League to purchase the Edmonton Oilers, and then on July 2, 2008, he was officially announced as the owner of the Edmonton Oilers during a Press Conference at Rexall Place, where he was presented with an Edmonton Oilers Jersey with the number \"08\" and his last name patched onto the back.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn June 2014, Katz Group announced<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=722586#&navid=EDM-search |title=Katz Group Names Bob Nicholson Vice-Chairman of New Sports & Entertainment Company &#124; NHL.com |website=Oilers.nhl.com |date=2014-06-13 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> that [[Bob Nicholson (ice hockey)|Bob Nicholson]] would join the organization as Vice-Chairman of [[Oilers Entertainment Group]] (OEG), a new sports and entertainment company that would manage the Katz Group\u2019s growing family of sports and entertainment assets, and operate [[Rogers Place]], the new home of the Edmonton Oilers.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn addition to the Oilers, OEG owns and operates the [[Edmonton Oil Kings]] (WHL), and [[Bakersfield Condors (AHL)|Bakersfield Condors]] (AHL) as well as Aquila Productions (film & production company). Nicholson was named<ref>{{cite web|title=Edmonton Oilers Press Release|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=764212|website=Oilers.nhl.com|publisher=NHL|accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> CEO of OEG in April 2015 and given responsibility for both business and hockey operations.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn April 2015, Katz announced a partnership<ref>{{cite web|last=Hipes |first=Patrick |url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/joel-silver-silver-pictures-entertainment-daryl-katz-hal-sadoff-1201416892/ |title=Joel Silver Forms Silver Pictures Entertainment & Taps Hal Sadoff As CEO |publisher=Deadline |date=2015-04-27 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> with [[Joel Silver]] to create Silver Pictures Entertainment \u2013 a new company that will develop, produce and provide or arrange financing for feature films, television and digital projects.  Katz\u2019 interests in the company fall under the OEG umbrella.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Rogers Place and Edmonton Ice District (former Arena District)==\nKatz has said he bought the Oilers because he saw Edmonton\u2019s need for a new arena as an opportunity to be the catalyst for the revitalization of Edmonton\u2019s downtown core.  Following public consultations and negotiations with the [[City of Edmonton]], Katz Group and the city agreed to a public-private partnership to build Rogers Place arena, which would see the city retain ownership of the new arena, and Katz Group operate it (under OEG). The City\u2019s portion of arena funding will be paid through a Community Revitalization Levy and will not result in any new cost to taxpayers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Funding Agreement |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/the-agreement.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712155036/http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/the-agreement.aspx |archivedate=2015-07-12 }}</ref>  Construction on the project began March 2014.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nSet to open in fall 2016, Rogers Place was marketed as one of North America\u2019s most advanced sports & entertainment venues, active year-round and featuring a 24,000 square foot grand entrance-way called the Winter Garden which can be used as public/private programmable space.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winter Garden |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/arena-winter-garden.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507151321/http://www.edmonton.ca/city_government/projects_redevelopment/arena-winter-garden.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-07 }}</ref>\n\nWith Rogers Place at its core, Katz Group has begun construction of the Edmonton Arena District (EAD),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=80301 |title=Edmonton Downtown Arena and Entertainment District - Edmonton Oilers - News |website=Oilers.nhl.com |date=2012-05-17 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> slated to be Canada\u2019s largest mixed-use sports and entertainment development. The EAD will cover 25 contiguous acres of downtown Edmonton, and feature a 50,000 square foot public plaza, two office towers, a JW Marriott Hotel, a Gateway casino, over 1,000 luxury condos and rental apartments, and 270,000 square feet of retail space at a total cost of approximately $2.5 billion.  In 2014, it was announced that the City of Edmonton and [[Stantec]] would be the major tenants of the two respective office towers. Stantec's tower will be the tallest in Edmonton at 69 storeys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/62-storey-tower-to-be-built-in-downtown-edmonton-1.2747702 |title=62-storey tower to be built in downtown Edmonton - Edmonton - CBC News |website=Cbc.ca |date=2014-08-26 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Edmonton Arena District was formally renamed the [[Ice District]] on July 13, 2015.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn October 2006 Katz announced a $7 million donation to the University of Alberta Faculty of Pharmacy and Pharmaceutical Sciences and Faculty of Law. Matched by the province, the gift was the largest donation ever to a Canadian pharmacy school. The west wing of the Health Research Innovation Facility at the corner of 87th Avenue and 114th Street in Edmonton has been named The Katz Group Centre for Pharmacy and Health Research. In 2009 Katz donated $20 Million to [[Mount Sinai Hospital in Toronto]] and founded The Daryl A Katz Centre For Urgent And Critical Care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mshfoundation.ca/page.aspx?pid=424 |title=Mount Sinai Hospital Foundation of Toronto |website=Mshfoundation.ca |date=2014-01-20 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref> Katz has also given \"millions\" to the [[Stollery Children's Hospital]] in Edmonton, as well as supporting public events.<ref name=\"tsn.ca\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100524113236/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=322173]</ref>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2010, Katz and his wife have donated \"over $50 million\" to organizations and institutions across Canada.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121110160305/http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=a34af8e9-099d-4175-8c35-d81d4364b32f&sponsor= ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/travel/Daryl+Renee+Katz+donate+Gallery+Alberta/2491478/story.html |title=Daryl and Renee Katz donate $500,000 to Art Gallery of Alberta |website=Edmontonjournal.com |date=2010-01-27 |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKatz' [[net worth]] is reported at US$3.5 billion which makes him the 12th wealthiest person in Canada.<ref name=ForbesBillionaires/>\n\nKatz is married to Renee Gouin.<ref name=ArchivesCanada />  She is the daughter of [[Jean Ivan Gouin|Jean Yvon (Ivan) Gouin]]. In 1952, her father founded the North American Construction Group which became one of the largest mining and heavy construction companies in Canada.<ref>[http://www2.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/insight/story.html?id=25433850-1494-4be2-a74e-8ba819d6465c&p=1   He has two kids: Chlo\u00e9 Katz and Harrison Katz. They both started a new organization in 2015 called Hockey Helps Kids.  The organization was meant for 4 junior high school to make a video and then it would be showed at Oiler games and people would vote on their favourite school. The school that wins will receive $25,000 for their charity. The three other schools would get $10 000 for their charity and $5000 for their school.  The schools were also given a team captain which were one of the Oilers players. The captains for 2015/2016 were Connor McDavid, Jordan Eberle, Taylor Hall, and Ryan Nugent-Hopkins. The winners of 2015/2016 were Kilarny school with captain Connor McDavid. ''Edmonton Journal'': \"Daryl Katz: reclusive billionaire\" by Rick McConnell, John MacKinnon and Gary Lamphier] December 17, 2012 \\ ''\"Katz married Renee Gouin, a member of one of Edmonton's wealthiest families...Her parents, Jean Yvon and Carol Gouin, had started a Spruce Grove company called North American Construction Group in 1952, which they built into one of the largest mining and heavy construction companies in Canada\"''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/remembering/obituary.aspx?n=jean-yvon-gouin-ivan&pid=98838924#fbLoggedOut |title=Jean Gouin Obituary - Vancouver, BC &#124; Remembering |website=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>\n\nKatz's riverfront mansion at 4 Valleyview Point in the [[Parkview, Edmonton|Parkview neighbourhood]], is one of the largest houses in Edmonton at {{convert|25000|sqft|m2}}, and estimated to be worth C$13 million.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gordon Kent |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/business/real-estate/property-values-on-the-rise-in-edmonton |title=Top homes worth a bundle in Edmonton millionaire\u2019s market |newspaper=[[Edmonton Journal]] |date= |accessdate=2017-01-29}}</ref>  The property overlooks the [[North Saskatchewan River valley parks system|North Saskatchewan river valley]], [[Hawrelak Park]], and the downtown city skyline and is easily visible and instantly recognizable from the river valley's many trails.  The [[great room]] is clad floor-to-ceiling in {{convert|90|kg|adj=on}} blocks of Italian [[limestone]] and with {{convert|9|m|adj=on}}-high windows framing a view of downtown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communities.canada.com/edmontonjournal/blogs/hockey/archive/2008/02/06/daryl-katz-may-be-a-caped-crusader-but-he-is-no-bruce-wayne.aspx |title=Tonic to some, bitter pill to others: Daryl Katz's 25,000-square-foot mansion demands--and gets--attention, both pro and con |accessdate=2008-06-04 |author=Shawn Ohler |date=May 21, 2006 |work=The [[Edmonton Journal]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610165109/http://communities.canada.com/edmontonjournal/blogs/hockey/archive/2008/02/06/daryl-katz-may-be-a-caped-crusader-but-he-is-no-bruce-wayne.aspx |archivedate=2008-06-10 }}</ref> The property also features two swimming pools. For his children, Katz bought the multimillion-dollar house next to his, demolished it, and built a practice hockey rink.\n\nKatz also owns homes in the US and British Columbia, the latter reportedly a near carbon copy of his Edmonton home.<ref name=\"tsn.ca\"/>\n\nIt was reported in May 2019 that Katz had had a \"potentially life-threatening infection\" for a few years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/edmonton-oilers-daryl-katz-illness-1.5126650|title=Edmonton Oilers owner Daryl Katz dealing with life-threatening illness, team says}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.katzgroup.ca/ The Katz Group of Companies]\n\n{{Katz Group}}\n{{Edmonton Oilers}}\n{{NHLOwners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katz, Daryl}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Katz Group]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Canadian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Canadian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Canadian investors]]\n[[Category:Canadian pharmaceutical industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Oilers executives]]\n[[Category:Jewish Canadian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Lawyers in Alberta]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League executives]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League owners]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta Faculty of Law alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daryl_Katz"}
{"title_page": "Hingalganj, North 24 Parganas", "text_new": "{{About|the census town in West Bengal, India|1 its namesake community development block|Hingalganj|2 its namesake assembly constituency|Hingalganj (Vidhan Sabha constituency)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                               = Hingalganj\n| native_name                        = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per Wikipedia:INDISCRIPT policy -->\n| native_name_lang                   = \n| other_name                         = \n| nickname                           = \n| settlement_type                    = Census Town\n| image_skyline                      = \n| image_alt                          = \n| image_caption                      = \n| pushpin_map                        = India West Bengal # India \n| pushpin_label_position             =\t\n| pushpin_map_alt                    =    \n| pushpin_map_caption                = Location in West Bengal, India \n| coordinates                        = {{coord|22.470803|N|88.983346|E|display=inline,title}} \n| subdivision_type               = Country      \n| subdivision_name               = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1              = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1              = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2              = [[List of districts of West Bengal|District]]\n| subdivision_name2              = [[North 24 Parganas]]\n| established_title              = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date               = \n| founder                        = \n| named_for                      = \n| government_type                = \n| governing_body                 = \n| unit_pref                      = Metric\n| area_footnotes                 = \n| area_rank                      = \n| area_total_km2                 = \n| elevation_footnotes            = \n| elevation_m                    = \n| population_total               = 8,179\n| population_as_of               = 2011\n| population_rank                = \n| population_density_km2         = auto\n| population_demonym             = \n| population_footnotes           = \n| demographics_type1             = Languages\n| demographics1_title1           = Official\n| demographics1_info1            = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1                      = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                    = +5:30\n| postal_code_type               = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                    = 743435 (Hingalganj)\n| area_code_type                 = Telephone/[[Subscriber trunk dialing|STD]] code\n| area_code                      = 03217\n| blank1_name_sec1               = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1               = [[Basirhat (Lok Sabha constituency)|Basirhat]]\n| blank2_name_sec1               = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1               = [[Hingalganj (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Hingalganj]]\n| website                        = {{URL|north24parganas.nic.in/}} \n| footnotes                      = \n}}\n'''Hingalganj''' is a [[census town]] in [[Hingalganj]] CD Block in [[Basirhat subdivision]] of [[North 24 Parganas district]] in the state of [[West Bengal]], [[India]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Hingalganj came after the name of Tillman Henkel, district judge and magistrate in Jessore district from 1781. He developed the settlement there.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ijsr.net/archive/v4i1/SUB15105.pdf | title =  Different Issues in Boarder Area of Sundarban Deltaic Rural Area with Special References to Hingalgaj Block, North 24 Parganas, West Bengal, India | first = Bikash| last = Mondal  | publisher =  International Journal of Science and Research (IJSR), 2013 |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Police station==\nHingalganj police station serves a population of 112,941. It has jurisdiction over Hingalganj CD Block.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://n24pgspolice.in/home/police-station.php |title =  North 24 Parganas Dist. Police| work= Know Your Police Station|publisher=  District Police| accessdate = 6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#ffffcc; color:black; width:20em; max-width: 25%;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n! style=\"background-color:#cccccc;\" | Hingalganj\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n... Hingalganj, a block headquarters some 100 km from Calcutta. A ribbon-like road threads through the tree-clad villages on this island in the Sunderbans delta, empty of traffic except for an occasional motorcycle-driven cart laden with passengers, the lone local transport. At midday, the only sound you hear is the chirping of invisible crickets. Hingalganj, clearly, looks idyllic.\n\nSuddenly, an armed Border Security Force squad emerges from a roadside bamboo grove. Further on, near what looks like a village square, another group of border guards marches by, fingers on the triggers of the guns hanging from their shoulders. In front of the local police station, a constable stands guard with an automatic rifle, an unusual sight in a rural police station in West Bengal.\n\nBut then, Hingalganj is not just another rural town in Bengal. Perched on India's border with Bangladesh, Hingalganj, in North 24 Parganas district, is now a gateway to terror, a place the security forces and intelligence agents are keeping a sharp eye on.\n\n- [[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]], 3 September 2006<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.telegraphindia.com/1060903/asp/opinion/story_6691043.asp| title = Bengal, the new terror hub, Police recognise the threat to Calcutta   | publisher =  The Telegraph, 3 September 2006 |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==CD Block HQ==\nThe headquarters of Hingalganj CD Block are located at Hingalganj.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1911_PART_A_DCHB_NORTH%20TWENTY%20FOUR%20PARGANAS.pdf |title = District Census Handbook North Twenty Four Parganas, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work = Map of North Twenty Four Parganas with CD Block HQs and Police Stations (on the fifth page) | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs per the [[2011 Census of India]], Hingalganj town had a total population of 8,179, of which 4,129 (50%) were males and 4,050 (50%) were females. Population below 6 years was 812. The total number of literates in Hingalganj was 5,503 (74.70% of the population over 6 years).<ref name=census2011>{{cite web| url = http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/cdb_pca_census/Houselisting-housing-WB.html |title = C.D. Block Wise Primary Census Abstract Data(PCA) | work= West Bengal \u2013 District-wise CD Blocks|publisher= Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India  | accessdate = 11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThis is what a two-wheeler rider wrote after a visit to the area in 2014: \u201c[[Hasnabad]] is a border town (with Bangladesh) and also the last significant town in the area. Vigil is very high. Any one travelling to that area is advised to have at least one photo ID proof so that could be showed to the BSF. After crossing the Ichhamati River, it\u2019s a 15 odd kms ride to Hingalganj \u2013 a small sleepy place of around 5 sq kms. Road is not wide but save 1 km, is a pleasure to ride.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.xbhp.com/talkies/tourer/30386-my-ride-hemngar-sunderbans-where-forest-meets-rivers.html | title =  My ride to Hemnagar, Sundarbans, where the forest meet the rivers| publisher =  XBHP |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 684 m long bridge across the Katakhali at Hasnabad was opened to public in March 2019, linking Hingalganj with Hasnabad. Lebukhali, the last point up to which motorised transport can reach is now directly connected to Kolkata and other places.<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.anandabazar.com/district/24-paraganas/peaple-eagerly-waiting-for-hasnabad-bridge-1.951276 | title = \u09b8\u09c7\u09a4\u09c1 \u0989\u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09cb\u09a7\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a6\u09bf\u09a8 \u0997\u09c1\u09a8\u099b\u09c7 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7  |trans-title=People counting days left for inauguration of bridge | work = | language = bn | publisher = Ananda Bazar Patrika | date = 14 February 2019 | accessdate = 12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Hingalganj Mahavidyalaya]] was established at Hingalganj in 2005. It is a co-educational institution affiliated with the [[West Bengal State University]] and offers honours courses in Bengali, English, Sanskrit, geography and education, and a general course in arts.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://hingalganjmahavidyalaya.in/  | title = Hingalganj Mahavidyalaya  | publisher = HM |accessdate =  8 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.collegeadmission.in/HingalganjMahavidyalaya/HingalganjMahavidyalaya.shtml | title = Hingalganj Mahaviyalaya  | publisher = College Admission  |accessdate =  8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nHingalganj High School is a Bengali-medium co-educational school. It was established in 1948. It has arrangements for teaching from Class VI to XII.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.icbse.com/schools/hingalganj-high-school-h-s/19111502203 | title = Hingalgabj High School (HS)  | publisher =  ICBSE |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Healthcare==\nHingalganj has a  [[Primary Health Centre (India)|primary health centre]] with 6 beds.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbhealth.gov.in/ | title = Health & Family Welfare Department | work= Health Statistics  | publisher = Government of West Bengal  |accessdate =  11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{North 24 Parganas District}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in North 24 Parganas district]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the census town in West Bengal, India|1 its namesake community development block|Hingalganj|2 its namesake assembly constituency|Hingalganj (Vidhan Sabha constituency)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                               = Hingalganj\n| native_name                        = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per Wikipedia:INDISCRIPT policy -->\n| native_name_lang                   = \n| other_name                         = \n| nickname                           = \n| settlement_type                    = Census Town\n| image_skyline                      = \n| image_alt                          = \n| image_caption                      = \n| pushpin_map                        = India West Bengal # India \n| pushpin_label_position             =\t\n| pushpin_map_alt                    =    \n| pushpin_map_caption                = Location in West Bengal, India \n| coordinates                        = {{coord|22.470803|N|88.983346|E|display=inline,title}} \n| subdivision_type               = Country      \n| subdivision_name               = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1              = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1              = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2              = [[List of districts of West Bengal|District]]\n| subdivision_name2              = [[North 24 Parganas]]\n| established_title              = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date               = \n| founder                        = \n| named_for                      = \n| government_type                = \n| governing_body                 = \n| unit_pref                      = Metric\n| area_footnotes                 = \n| area_rank                      = \n| area_total_km2                 = \n| elevation_footnotes            = \n| elevation_m                    = \n| population_total               = 8,179\n| population_as_of               = 2011\n| population_rank                = \n| population_density_km2         = auto\n| population_demonym             = \n| population_footnotes           = \n| demographics_type1             = Languages\n| demographics1_title1           = Official\n| demographics1_info1            = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1                      = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                    = +5:30\n| postal_code_type               = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                    = 743435 (Hingalganj)\n| area_code_type                 = Telephone/[[Subscriber trunk dialing|STD]] code\n| area_code                      = 03217\n| blank1_name_sec1               = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1               = [[Basirhat (Lok Sabha constituency)|Basirhat]]\n| blank2_name_sec1               = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1               = [[Hingalganj (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Hingalganj]]\n| website                        = {{URL|north24parganas.nic.in/}} \n| footnotes                      = \n}}\n'''Hingalganj''' is a [[census town]] in [[Hingalganj]] CD Block in [[Basirhat subdivision]] of [[North 24 Parganas district]] in the state of [[West Bengal]], [[India]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name Hingalganj came after the name of Tillman Henkel, district judge and magistrate in Jessore district from 1781. He developed the settlement there.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ijsr.net/archive/v4i1/SUB15105.pdf | title =  Different Issues in Boarder Area of Sundarban Deltaic Rural Area with Special References to Hingalgaj Block, North 24 Parganas, West Bengal, India | first = Bikash| last = Mondal  | publisher =  International Journal of Science and Research (IJSR), 2013 |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Police station==\nHingalganj police station serves a population of 112,941. It has jurisdiction over Hingalganj CD Block.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://n24pgspolice.in/home/police-station.php |title =  North 24 Parganas Dist. Police| work= Know Your Police Station|publisher=  District Police| accessdate = 6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#ffffcc; color:black; width:20em; max-width: 25%;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n! style=\"background-color:#cccccc;\" | Hingalganj\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n... Hingalganj, a block headquarters some 100 km from Calcutta. A ribbon-like road threads through the tree-clad villages on this island in the Sunderbans delta, empty of traffic except for an occasional motorcycle-driven cart laden with passengers, the lone local transport. At midday, the only sound you hear is the chirping of invisible crickets. Hingalganj, clearly, looks idyllic.\n\nSuddenly, an armed Border Security Force squad emerges from a roadside bamboo grove. Further on, near what looks like a village square, another group of border guards marches by, fingers on the triggers of the guns hanging from their shoulders. In front of the local police station, a constable stands guard with an automatic rifle, an unusual sight in a rural police station in West Bengal.\n\nBut then, Hingalganj is not just another rural town in Bengal. Perched on India\u2019s border with Bangladesh, Hingalganj, in North 24 Parganas district, is now a gateway to terror, a place the security forces and intelligence agents are keeping a sharp eye on.\n\n- [[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]], 3 September 2006<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.telegraphindia.com/1060903/asp/opinion/story_6691043.asp| title = Bengal, the new terror hub, Police recognise the threat to Calcutta   | publisher =  The Telegraph, 3 September 2006 |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==CD Block HQ==\nThe headquarters of Hingalganj CD Block are located at Hingalganj.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1911_PART_A_DCHB_NORTH%20TWENTY%20FOUR%20PARGANAS.pdf |title = District Census Handbook North Twenty Four Parganas, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work = Map of North Twenty Four Parganas with CD Block HQs and Police Stations (on the fifth page) | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAs per the [[2011 Census of India]], Hingalganj town had a total population of 8,179, of which 4,129 (50%) were males and 4,050 (50%) were females. Population below 6 years was 812. The total number of literates in Hingalganj was 5,503 (74.70% of the population over 6 years).<ref name=census2011>{{cite web| url = http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/cdb_pca_census/Houselisting-housing-WB.html |title = C.D. Block Wise Primary Census Abstract Data(PCA) | work= West Bengal \u2013 District-wise CD Blocks|publisher= Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India  | accessdate = 11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThis is what a two-wheeler rider wrote after a visit to the area in 2014: \u201c[[Hasnabad]] is a border town (with Bangladesh) and also the last significant town in the area. Vigil is very high. Any one travelling to that area is advised to have at least one photo ID proof so that could be showed to the BSF. After crossing the Ichhamati River, it\u2019s a 15 odd kms ride to Hingalganj \u2013 a small sleepy place of around 5 sq kms. Road is not wide but save 1 km, is a pleasure to ride.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.xbhp.com/talkies/tourer/30386-my-ride-hemngar-sunderbans-where-forest-meets-rivers.html | title =  My ride to Hemnagar, Sundarbans, where the forest meet the rivers| publisher =  XBHP |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 684 m long bridge across the Katakhali at Hasnabad was opened to public in March 2019, linking Hingalganj with Hasnabad. Lebukhali, the last point up to which motorised transport can reach is now directly connected to Kolkata and other places.<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.anandabazar.com/district/24-paraganas/peaple-eagerly-waiting-for-hasnabad-bridge-1.951276 | title = \u09b8\u09c7\u09a4\u09c1 \u0989\u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09cb\u09a7\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a6\u09bf\u09a8 \u0997\u09c1\u09a8\u099b\u09c7 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7  |trans-title=People counting days left for inauguration of bridge | work = | language = bn | publisher = Ananda Bazar Patrika | date = 14 February 2019 | accessdate = 12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Hingalganj Mahavidyalaya]] was established at Hingalganj in 2005. It is a co-educational institution affiliated with the [[West Bengal State University]] and offers honours courses in Bengali, English, Sanskrit, geography and education, and a general course in arts.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://hingalganjmahavidyalaya.in/  | title = Hingalganj Mahavidyalaya  | publisher = HM |accessdate =  8 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.collegeadmission.in/HingalganjMahavidyalaya/HingalganjMahavidyalaya.shtml | title = Hingalganj Mahaviyalaya  | publisher = College Admission  |accessdate =  8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nHingalganj High School is a Bengali-medium co-educational school. It was established in 1948. It has arrangements for teaching from Class VI to XII.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.icbse.com/schools/hingalganj-high-school-h-s/19111502203 | title = Hingalgabj High School (HS)  | publisher =  ICBSE |accessdate =  12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Healthcare==\nHingalganj has a  [[Primary Health Centre (India)|primary health centre]] with 6 beds.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbhealth.gov.in/ | title = Health & Family Welfare Department | work= Health Statistics  | publisher = Government of West Bengal  |accessdate =  11 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{North 24 Parganas District}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in North 24 Parganas district]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolice station:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hingalganj,_North_24_Parganas"}
{"title_page": "24th United States Congress", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox United States Congress\n|number         = 24th\n|image          = USCapitol1827A.gif\n|imagename      = [[United States Capitol]]\n|imagedate      = 1827\n|start          = March 4, 1835\n|end            = March 4, 1837\n|vp             = [[Martin Van Buren]] (J)\n|pro tem        = [[William R. King]] (J)\n|speaker        = [[James K. Polk]] (J)\n|senators       = 52\n|reps           = 242\n|delegates      = 3\n|s-majority     = [[Jacksonian Party (United States)|Jacksonian]]\n|h-majority     = [[Jacksonian Party (United States)|Jacksonian]]\n|sessionnumber1 = 1st \n|sessionstart1  = December 7, 1835\n|sessionend1    = July 4, 1836\n|sessionnumber2 = 2nd \n|sessionstart2  = December 5, 1836\n|sessionend2    = March 3, 1837\n|previous       = 23rd\n|next           = 25th\n}}\nThe '''Twenty-fourth United States Congress''' was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the [[United States Senate]] and the [[United States House of Representatives]]. It met in [[Washington, D.C.]] from March 4, 1835, to March 4, 1837, during the seventh and eighth years of [[Andrew Jackson]]'s [[Presidency of Andrew Jackson|presidency]].  The apportionment of seats in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] was based on the [[United States Census, 1830|Fifth Census of the United States in 1830]]. Both chambers had a [[Jacksonian Party (United States)|Jacksonian]] majority.\n{{TOClimit|2}}\n\n== Major events ==\n{{Main|1835 in the United States|1836 in the United States|1837 in the United States}}\n* December 28, 1835: The [[Second Seminole War]] began. [[Seminole]] fighter [[Osceola]] and his warriors attack government agent Thompson outside Fort King in central [[Florida]].\n* 1835: [[Toledo War]] fought between [[Ohio]] and [[Michigan Territory]] over the [[Toledo, Ohio|city of Toledo]] and the [[Toledo Strip]].\n* February 3, 1836: [[United States Whig Party]] held its first convention in [[Albany, New York]].\n* February 23, 1836: Siege of the [[Alamo Mission in San Antonio|Alamo]] began in [[San Antonio, Texas]].\n* July 11, 1836: President [[Andrew Jackson]] issued the [[Specie Circular]], beginning the failure of the land speculation economy that would lead to the [[Panic of 1837]].\n* July 13, 1836: United States [[patent]] #1 was granted after filing 9,957 unnumbered patents.\n* November 3 \u2013 December 7, 1836: [[1836 United States presidential election|1836 presidential election]]: [[Martin Van Buren]] defeated [[William Henry Harrison]], but [[United States Electoral College|Virginia's electors]] refused to vote for Van Buren's running mate, [[Richard Mentor Johnson]], thereby denying victory to any [[Vice President of the United States|vice presidential]] candidate.\n* December 4, 1836: [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]] held its first national convention, in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].\n* December 15, 1836: [[1836 U.S. Patent Office fire]]\n* February 8, 1837: Richard Mentor Johnson defeated [[Francis Granger]] to win the (first and to date only) [[contingent election]] for Vice President of the United States.<ref>{{cite web| title=''Cong. Globe'', 24th Cong., 2nd Sess. 166 (1837)| url=http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llcg&fileName=003/llcg003.db&recNum=181| work=A Century of Lawmaking for a New Nation: U.S. Congressional Documents and Debates, 1774\u20131875| publisher=[[Library of Congress]]| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=August 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/The_Senate_Elects_A_Vice_President.htm| title=The Senate Elects a Vice President| publisher=Office of the Secretary of the Senate| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Major legislation==\n{{Main|List of United States federal legislation, 1789\u20131901}}\n* July 4, 1836: [[Patent Act of 1836]], {{USStatute|24|357|5|117}}\n{{dm|date=February 2020}}\n\n== Treaties ==\n\n* December 29, 1835: [[Treaty of New Echota]] signed, ceding all the lands of the [[Cherokee]] east of the Mississippi to the United States\n\n== States admitted and territories formed ==\n\n*June 15, 1836: [[Arkansas]] [[Admission to the Union|admitted]] as the 25th state {{USStat|5|50}}\n*January 26, 1837: [[Michigan]] admitted as the 26th state {{USStat|5|144}}; contingently approved June 15, 1836 {{USStat|5|49}}\n*July 3, 1837: [[Wisconsin Territory]] established; approved April 20, 1836 {{USStat|5|10}}\n\n==Party summary==\nThe count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress. Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the \"[[#Changes in membership|Changes in membership]]\" section.\n\n=== Senate ===\nDuring this congress two Senate seats were added for each of the new states of Arkansas and Michigan.<ref name=Arkansas>{{USStat|5|50}}</ref><ref name=Michigan>{{USStat|5|144}}</ref>\n{{US Congress party summary\n| congress           = 24\n\n| party1             = Anti-Jacksonian\n| abb1               = AJ\n| seats1_last        = 26\n| seats1_begin       = 24\n| seats1_end         = 19\n| seats1_next        = 19\n| note1_next         = as [[Whig party (United States)|Whig]]s\n\n| party2             = Jacksonian\n| abb2               = J\n| seats2_last        = 20\n| seats2_begin       = 21\n| seats2_end         = 31\n| seats2_next        = 33\n| note2_next         = as [[Democratic party (United States)|Democrat]]s\n| shading2_next      = Democratic\n\n| party3             = Nullifier\n| abb3               = N\n| seats3_last        = 2\n| seats3_begin       = 2\n| seats3_end         = 2\n| seats3_next        = 0\n\n| seats_vacant_last  = 0\n| seats_vacant_begin = 1\n| seats_vacant_end   = 0\n| seats_vacant_next  = 0\n\n}}\n\n===House of Representatives===\nDuring this congress one House seat was added for each of the new states of Arkansas and Michigan.<ref name=Arkansas/><ref name=Michigan/>\n{{US Congress party summary\n| congress           = 24\n\n| party1             = Anti-Jacksonian\n| abb1               = AJ\n| seats1_last        = 64\n| seats1_begin       = 75\n| seats1_end         = 79\n| seats1_next        = 100\n| note1_next         = as [[Whig party (United States)|Whig]]s\n\n| party2             = Anti-Masonic\n| abb2               = AM\n| seats2_last        = 26\n| seats2_begin       = 16\n| seats2_end         = 15\n| seats2_next        = 7\n\n| party3             = Jacksonian\n| abb3               = J\n| seats3_last        = 141\n| seats3_begin       = 140\n| seats3_end         = 139\n| seats3_next        = 121\n| note3_next         = as [[Democratic party (United States)|Democrat]]s\n| shading3_next      = Democratic\n\n| party4             = Nullifier\n| abb4               = N\n| seats4_last        = 8\n| seats4_begin       = 7\n| seats4_end         = 7\n| seats4_next        = 6\n\n| party5             = States' Rights\n| abb5               = SR\n| seats5_last        = 0\n| seats5_begin       = 0\n| seats5_end         = 1\n| seats5_next        = 0\n\n| seats_vacant_last  = 1\n| seats_vacant_begin = 2\n| seats_vacant_end   = 1\n| seats_vacant_next  = 0\n\n}}\n\n==Leadership==\n{{multiple image\n| align         =\n| direction     =\n| width         =\n| caption_align = center\n| header_align  = center\n| header        = <big>Senate leadership</big>\n| image1        = Van Buren.jpg\n| width1        = 150\n| alt1          = Martin Van Buren\n| caption1      = '''[[President of the United States Senate|Senate President]]'''<br/>[[Martin Van Buren]]\n| image2        = William Rufus DeVane King 1839 portrait.jpg\n| width2        = 140\n| alt2          = William R. King\n| caption2      = '''[[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|President pro tempore]]'''<br/>[[William R. King]]\n}}\n\n=== Senate ===\n* [[President of the United States Senate|President]]: [[Martin Van Buren]] (J)\n* [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|President pro tempore]]: [[William R. King]] (J)\n\n=== House of Representatives ===\n* [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]]:  [[James K. Polk]] (J)\n\n==Members==\nThis list is arranged by chamber, then by state. Senators are listed by class, and Representatives are listed by district.\n\n:''[[#House of Representatives_3|Skip to House of Representatives]], below''\n\n===Senate===\nSenators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress. Preceding the names in the list below are [[Classes of United States Senators|Senate class numbers]], which indicate the cycle of their election. In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1838; Class 2 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1840; and Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1836.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Alabama|Alabama]] ====\n*2. [[William R. King|William R. D. King]] (J)\n*3. [[Gabriel Moore]] (AJ)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Arkansas|Arkansas]] ====\n*2. [[William Savin Fulton|William S. Fulton]] (J), from September 18, 1836 (newly admitted state)\n*3. [[Ambrose Hundley Sevier|Ambrose H. Sevier]] (J), from September 18, 1836 (newly admitted state)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Connecticut|Connecticut]] ====\n*1. [[Nathan Smith (senator)|Nathan Smith]] (AJ), until December 6, 1835\n** [[John Milton Niles|John M. Niles]] (J), from December 21, 1835\n*3. [[Gideon Tomlinson]] (AJ)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Delaware|Delaware]] ====\n*1. [[Arnold Naudain]] (AJ), until June 16, 1836\n** [[Richard H. Bayard]] (AJ), from June 17, 1836\n*2. [[John M. Clayton]] (AJ), until December 29, 1836\n** [[Thomas Clayton]] (AJ), from January 9, 1837\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Georgia|Georgia]] ====\n*2. [[John Pendleton King|John P. King]] (J)\n*3. [[Alfred Cuthbert]] (J)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Illinois|Illinois]] ====\n*2. [[John McCracken Robinson|John M. Robinson]] (J)\n*3. [[Elias Kane|Elias K. Kane]] (J), until December 12, 1835\n** [[William Lee D. Ewing|William L. D. Ewing]] (J), from December 30, 1835\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Indiana|Indiana]] ====\n*1. [[John Tipton]] (J)\n*3. [[William Hendricks]] (AJ)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Kentucky|Kentucky]] ====\n*2. [[John J. Crittenden]] (AJ)\n*3. [[Henry Clay]] (AJ)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Louisiana|Louisiana]] ====\n*2. [[Robert C. Nicholas]] (J), from January 13, 1836\n*3. [[Alexander Porter]] (AJ), until January 5, 1837\n** [[Alexander Mouton]] (J), from January 12, 1837\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Maine|Maine]] ====\n*1. [[Ether Shepley]] (J), until March 3, 1836\n** [[Judah Dana]] (J), from December 7, 1836\n*2. [[John Ruggles]] (J)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Maryland|Maryland]] ====\n*1. [[Joseph Kent]] (AJ)\n*3. [[Robert Henry Goldsborough|Robert H. Goldsborough]] (AJ), until October 5, 1836\n** [[John S. Spence]] (AJ), from December 31, 1836\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] ====\n*1. [[Daniel Webster]] (AJ)\n*2. [[John Davis (Massachusetts Governor)|John Davis]] (AJ)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Michigan|Michigan]] ====\n*1. [[Lucius Lyon]] (J), from January 26, 1837 (newly admitted state)\n*2. [[John Norvell]] (J), from January 26, 1837 (newly admitted state)\n{{col-break}}\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Mississippi|Mississippi]] ====\n*1. [[John Black (U.S. Senator)|John Black]] (AJ)\n*2. [[Robert J. Walker]] (J)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Missouri|Missouri]] ====\n*1. [[Thomas Hart Be